Study authors said this “suggests that the largest number of unwanted pregnancies in the country may be the result of men and women being unable to control contraception.”

One hundred twelve males between the ages of 18 and 60 were surveyed alongside their spouses. Sixty percent of men and 80 percent of women had used contraception to control fertility, predominantly because of an unwanted birth. A similar number of men and women described an encounter with a pregnancied partner or a past unwanted birth as a catalyst for their own contraception use.

Common reasons for contraceptive action included previous illness, witnessing the birth of a child, poor health of the partner, lack of physical attraction, concern about the economic burden of a newborn and fear of the prejudice that could come in getting a job because of having a child.

Out of a total of 295 pregnancies, 135 were unintended, including one made by a homosexual act and three impregnated by rape. Half the men and women identified risk to the health of a partner as a motivating catalyst to pregnancy control. Twenty five percent identified incorrect use of the method as the reason.

About 15 percent of men and women said it was highly probable that the pregnancy control method had failed, and an additional of 10 men and seven women said it was likely.

Study authors predict a shift in contraceptive practice as demand for contraceptive technologies will dramatically increase
